%I A073828 #13 May 09 2026 00:26:33
%S A073828 2,2,3,13,125411328001,
%T A073828 69113789582492712943486800506462734562847413501952000000000000001
%N A073828 Primes of the form 1 + 0!*1!*2!*...*k! (subsequence of A019515).
%C A073828 a(4) = 125411328001 and the 65-digit a(5) have been certified prime with Primo. Any additional terms are too big to include here. a(3) = 13 and a(4) have twin primes, 11 and 125411327999 (also certified prime with Primo). No other primes of the form 0!*1!*2!*...*k! - 1 exist for k < 108.
%D A073828 Ryser, H. J. Combinatorial Mathematics. Buffalo, NY: Math. Assoc. Amer., p. 53, 1963.
%H A073828 Micha Fleuren, <a href="https://fs.unm.edu/SmFactProd.txt">Smarandache Factorial Products</a>.
%F A073828 a(n) = 1 + 0!*1!*2!*...*A073827(n)!.
%e A073828 a(0) = 1 + 0! (0=A073827(0)) = 1 + 1 = 2.
%e A073828 a(1) = 1 + 0!*1! (1=A073827(1)) = 1 + 1*1 = 2.
%e A073828 a(4) = 1 + 0!*1!*2!*3!*4!*5!*6!*7! (7=A073827(4)) = 1 + 1*1*2*6*24*120*720*5040 = 125411328001.
%o A073828 (PARI) my(pr=1); for(n=0,115, pr=pr*n!; if(isprime(pr+1), print1(pr+1,", ")))
%Y A073828 Cf. A073827 (corresponding n), A000178 (superfactorials), A019515 (supersequence: superfactorials + 1), A000142 (factorials).
%K A073828 nonn,changed
%O A073828 1,1
%A A073828 _Rick L. Shepherd_, Aug 16 2002
